    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Advertising vs. Editorial</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gil Bassak letter on Oct 3 article holds Cable News Network is right to refuse advertisements of coalition opposing Government's efforts to stem global warming (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Cable News Network is right to refuse the advertisements of an automobile and energy industry coalition attempting to undercut the Government's efforts to stem global warming (news article, Oct. 3). As you report, when companies don't like what editors print, they sometimes threaten to pull their advertising or demand to preview editorial content (Business Day, Sept. 29).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Cable News Network is right to refuse the advertisements of an automobile and energy industry coalition attempting to undercut the Government's efforts to stem global warming (news article, Oct. 3). As you report, when companies don't like what editors print, they sometimes threaten to pull their advertising or demand to preview editorial content (Business Day, Sept. 29).</p>
        <p>How soon before this same industry coalition starts telling CNN to tone down its reports on the burning of fossil fuels? By refusing the advertisements, CNN maintains credibility with its viewers and avoids the corruption of corporate influence that has, unfortunately, come to pass for business as usual. Now if only our elected officials could show as much courage.</p>
        <p>GIL BASSAK  Ossining, N.Y., Oct. 3, 1997</p>
      </block>
